---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const articleSchema = {
 "@context": "https://schema.org",
 "@type": "Article",
 "headline": "English Grammar Basics: A Complete Guide for All Levels",
 "description": "Master English grammar from scratch. Learn tenses, sentence structure, parts of speech, and common patterns. Perfect for beginners and intermediate learners.",
 "author": {
 "@type": "Organization",
 "name": "LearnEnglish.Life"
 },
 "datePublished": "2026-01-10",
 "dateModified": "2026-04-13"
};

const faqSchema = {
 "@context": "https://schema.org",
 "@type": "FAQPage",
 "mainEntity": [
 {
 "@type": "Question",
 "name": "What is the fastest way to learn English grammar?",
 "acceptedAnswer": {
 "@type": "Answer",
 "text": "Combine short daily study sessions with active practice. Learn one grammar point at a time (for example, present simple tense), then write 5 sentences using it, read a short article that uses it, and speak it aloud. 20-30 minutes a day beats 3 hours on the weekend."
 }
 },
 {
 "@type": "Question",
 "name": "Can I learn English grammar without memorizing rules?",
 "acceptedAnswer": {
 "@type": "Answer",
 "text": "Partly. Input-based learning (reading and listening to lots of English) teaches you grammar patterns intuitively. But for faster progress, especially at B1 and B2 levels, combining input with explicit rule study produces the best results. Most learners benefit from knowing why a rule works, not just that it does."
 }
 },
 {
 "@type": "Question",
 "name": "How long does it take to master English grammar?",
 "acceptedAnswer": {
 "@type": "Answer",
 "text": "Reaching B2 grammar mastery typically takes 300-600 hours of focused study, or roughly 6-12 months with daily practice. Basic conversational grammar (A2 level) can be reached in 100-150 hours. Advanced fluency with complex structures like conditionals and subjunctives usually takes 2-3 years."
 }
 },
 {
 "@type": "Question",
 "name": "What are the most important grammar rules for beginners?",
 "acceptedAnswer": {
 "@type": "Answer",
 "text": "Focus on: (1) Subject-verb-object order, (2) Present simple vs present continuous, (3) Past simple for completed actions, (4) Articles a/an/the, (5) Common prepositions in/on/at, and (6) Basic question formation. These six areas cover most everyday communication."
 }
 },
 {
 "@type": "Question",
 "name": "Should I use a tutor to learn grammar or study alone?",
 "acceptedAnswer": {
 "@type": "Answer",
 "text": "Both work, but a tutor accelerates progress significantly. Self-study is enough for learning rules, but a tutor catches mistakes you would never notice alone and gives you speaking practice. A good hybrid is self-study plus 1-2 tutor lessons per week for correction and conversation."
 }
 }
 ]
};
---

<Base title="English Grammar Basics: A Complete Guide (2026)" description="Master English grammar from scratch. Learn tenses, sentence structure, parts of speech, and common patterns. Perfect for beginners and intermediate learners.">
 <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(articleSchema)} />
 <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

 <Header />
 
 <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
 <!-- Breadcrumb -->
 <nav class="text-sm text-slate-400 mb-4">
 <a href="/" class="hover:text-emerald-600">Home</a>
 <span class="mx-2">›</span>
 <a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-emerald-600">Study Guides</a>
 <span class="mx-2">›</span>
 <span class="text-gray-300">Grammar Basics</span>
 </nav>

 <!-- Hero -->
 <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-emerald-600 to-teal-600 rounded-2xl p-8 text-white mb-8">
 <span class="text-emerald-200 text-sm font-medium">Study Guide</span>
 <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mt-2 mb-4">English Grammar Basics</h1>
 <p class="text-emerald-100 text-lg mb-6">Everything you need to understand how English grammar works. From basic sentence structure to verb tenses, we've got you covered.</p>
 
 <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-4">
 <span class="bg-slate-900/60/20 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm">Beginner</span>
 <span class="bg-slate-900/60/20 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm">Intermediate</span>
 <span class="bg-slate-900/60/20 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm">45 min read</span>
 </div>
 </div>

 <!-- TL;DR -->
 <div class="bg-amber-950/60 border-l-4 border-amber-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg mb-8">
 <h2 class="font-semibold text-amber-200">Quick Summary</h2>
 <p class="text-amber-300">English grammar follows a few key patterns: subject + verb + object, consistent verb tenses, and proper use of articles. Master these basics, and you'll understand most English sentences.</p>
 </div>

 <AdUnit slot="guide-header" />

 <!-- Table of Contents -->
 <nav class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
 <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">In This Guide</h2>
 <ul class="space-y-2">
 <li><a href="#parts-of-speech" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">1. Parts of Speech</a></li>
 <li><a href="#sentence-structure" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">2. Basic Sentence Structure</a></li>
 <li><a href="#verb-tenses" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">3. Verb Tenses</a></li>
 <li><a href="#articles" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">4. Articles: a, an, the</a></li>
 <li><a href="#common-mistakes" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">5. Common Mistakes</a></li>
 </ul>
 </nav>

 <!-- Parts of Speech -->
 <section id="parts-of-speech" class="mb-10">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">1. Parts of Speech</h2>
 
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Nouns</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2">Words for people, places, things, or ideas.</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Examples: cat, London, happiness, John</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Verbs</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2">Action or state words.</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Examples: run, is, think, eat</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Adjectives</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2">Words that describe nouns.</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Examples: beautiful, tall, happy</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Adverbs</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2">Words that describe verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Examples: quickly, very, always</p>
 </div>
 </div>

 <div class="bg-slate-900/60 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-3">Example Sentence Breakdown</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-lg mb-2">"The <span class="text-emerald-400">quick</span>brown <span class="text-blue-400">fox</span> <span class="text-red-400">jumps</span> <span class="text-yellow-400">over</span>the lazy dog."</p>
 <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-3">
 <span class="bg-emerald-900/50 text-emerald-400 px-2 py-1 rounded text-xs">quick = adjective</span>
 <span class="bg-blue-900/50 text-blue-400 px-2 py-1 rounded text-xs">fox = noun</span>
 <span class="bg-red-900/50 text-red-400 px-2 py-1 rounded text-xs">jumps = verb</span>
 <span class="bg-yellow-900/50 text-yellow-400 px-2 py-1 rounded text-xs">over = preposition</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Sentence Structure -->
 <section id="sentence-structure" class="mb-10">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">2. Basic Sentence Structure</h2>
 
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-6 border border-neutral-700 mb-6">
 <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-emerald-400 mb-4">Subject + Verb + Object (SVO)</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4">The most common English sentence pattern:</p>
 
 <div class="space-y-3">
 <div class="flex items-center gap-4 p-3 bg-neutral-900 rounded-lg">
 <span class="bg-emerald-900/50 text-emerald-400 px-3 py-1 rounded">Subject</span>
 <span class="bg-red-900/50 text-red-400 px-3 py-1 rounded">Verb</span>
 <span class="bg-blue-900/50 text-blue-400 px-3 py-1 rounded">Object</span>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-center gap-4 p-3 bg-neutral-900 rounded-lg">
 <span class="text-white">I</span>
 <span class="text-slate-400">→</span>
 <span class="text-white">love</span>
 <span class="text-slate-400">→</span>
 <span class="text-white">English</span>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-center gap-4 p-3 bg-neutral-900 rounded-lg">
 <span class="text-white">She</span>
 <span class="text-slate-400">→</span>
 <span class="text-white">reads</span>
 <span class="text-slate-400">→</span>
 <span class="text-white">books</span>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-center gap-4 p-3 bg-neutral-900 rounded-lg">
 <span class="text-white">They</span>
 <span class="text-slate-400">→</span>
 <span class="text-white">played</span>
 <span class="text-slate-400">→</span>
 <span class="text-white">football</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Verb Tenses -->
 <section id="verb-tenses" class="mb-10">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">3. Verb Tenses</h2>
 
 <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
 <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
 <thead>
 <tr class="bg-emerald-900/50">
 <th class="text-left p-4 text-white">Tense</th>
 <th class="text-left p-4 text-white">Use</th>
 <th class="text-left p-4 text-white">Example</th>
 </tr>
 </thead>
 <tbody class="divide-y divide-neutral-700">
 <tr>
 <td class="p-4 text-emerald-400 font-semibold">Present Simple</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">Habits, facts, general truths</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">I <strong>work</strong>every day.</td>
 </tr>
 <tr class="bg-neutral-900">
 <td class="p-4 text-emerald-400 font-semibold">Past Simple</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">Completed actions in the past</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">I <strong>worked</strong>yesterday.</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
 <td class="p-4 text-emerald-400 font-semibold">Future Simple</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">Predictions, plans</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">I <strong>will work</strong>tomorrow.</td>
 </tr>
 <tr class="bg-neutral-900">
 <td class="p-4 text-emerald-400 font-semibold">Present Continuous</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">Actions happening now</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">I <strong>am working</strong>now.</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
 <td class="p-4 text-emerald-400 font-semibold">Present Perfect</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">Past actions with present results</td>
 <td class="p-4 text-neutral-300">I <strong>have worked</strong>here for 5 years.</td>
 </tr>
 </tbody>
 </table>
 </div>
 </section>

 <AdUnit slot="guide-mid" />

 <!-- Articles -->
 <section id="articles" class="mb-10">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">4. Articles: a, an, the</h2>
 
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-6">
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-yellow-400 mb-3">a / an</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-3">Indefinite articles. one of many</p>
 <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
 <p class="text-neutral-400"><strong class="text-white">a</strong>before consonant sounds:</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-300">a <strong>cat</strong>, a <strong>book</strong>, a <strong>university</strong></p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 mt-2"><strong class="text-white">an</strong>before vowel sounds:</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-300">an <strong>apple</strong>, an <strong>hour</strong>, an <strong>idea</strong></p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700 md:col-span-2">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-400 mb-3">the</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-3">Definite article. specific thing we both know</p>
 <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
 <p class="text-neutral-400"><strong class="text-white">the + singular noun</strong>when there's only one:</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-300">the <strong>sun</strong>, the <strong>Earth</strong>, the <strong>President</strong></p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 mt-2"><strong class="text-white">the + noun</strong>when both speaker and listener know what we're referring to:</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-300">"Where is <strong>the bathroom</strong>?"</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>

 <div class="bg-amber-950/60 border-l-4 border-amber-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-200 mb-2">Quick Tip</h3>
 <p class="text-amber-300 text-sm">The sound matters, not the letter! We say "a <strong>u</strong>niversity" (yu-), so it's "a university" not "an university." We say "an <strong>h</strong>our" (our-), so it's "an hour" not "a hour."</p>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Common Mistakes -->
 <section id="common-mistakes" class="mb-10">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">5. Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
 
 <div class="space-y-4">
 <div class="bg-red-900/30 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">Their vs There vs They're</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2"><strong>Their</strong> = possessive (their house), <strong>There</strong> = place (over there), <strong>They're</strong> = they are</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Correct: They're going to their house over there.</p>
 </div>
 
 <div class="bg-red-900/30 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">Your vs You're</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2"><strong>Your</strong> = possessive (your book), <strong>You're</strong> = you are</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Correct: You're going to love your new book.</p>
 </div>
 
 <div class="bg-red-900/30 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">Its vs It's</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2"><strong>Its</strong> = possessive (the cat licked its paw), <strong>It's</strong> = it is or it has</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Correct: It's a beautiful day, and the dog is enjoying its walk.</p>
 </div>

 <div class="bg-red-900/30 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">Subject-Verb Agreement</h3>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm mb-2">Singular subjects need singular verbs, plural subjects need plural verbs.</p>
 <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm italic">Correct: He <strong>likes</strong>coffee. They <strong>like</strong>coffee.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Practice Section -->
 <section class="bg-emerald-900/30 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Practice Exercises</h2>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4">Test your understanding with these quick exercises:</p>
 
 <div class="space-y-4">
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-lg p-4">
 <p class="text-white mb-2">1. Choose the correct sentence:</p>
 <label class="text-neutral-300 block mb-1"><input type="radio" name="q1">A) She don't like coffee.</label>
 <label class="text-emerald-400 block mb-1"><input type="radio" name="q1">B) She doesn't like coffee. </label>
 </div>
 
 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-lg p-4">
 <p class="text-white mb-2">2. Fill in the blank: "I have been learning English ___ three years."</p>
 <label class="text-emerald-400 block mb-1"><input type="radio" name="q2">A) for </label>
 <label class="text-neutral-300 block mb-1"><input type="radio" name="q2">B) since</label>
 </div>

 <div class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-lg p-4">
 <p class="text-white mb-2">3. Which sentence is correct?</p>
 <label class="text-neutral-300 block mb-1"><input type="radio" name="q3">A) I went to the store yesterday.</label>
 <label class="text-emerald-400 block mb-1"><input type="radio" name="q3">B) I goed to the store yesterday. </label>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Related Guides -->
 <section class="mb-8">
 <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Continue Learning</h2>
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
 <a href="/guides/common-english-mistakes/" class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-lg p-4 hover:border-emerald-500 border border-neutral-700 transition">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Common Mistakes</h3>
 <p class="text-sm text-neutral-400">Avoid the most frequent errors</p>
 </a>
 <a href="/guides/" class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-lg p-4 hover:border-emerald-500 border border-neutral-700 transition">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Vocabulary Building</h3>
 <p class="text-sm text-neutral-400">Expand your word power</p>
 </a>
 <a href="/reviews/" class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-lg p-4 hover:border-emerald-500 border border-neutral-700 transition">
 <h3 class="font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Find a Tutor</h3>
 <p class="text-sm text-neutral-400">Practice with native speakers</p>
 </a>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- AI Disclosure -->
 <div class="text-xs text-slate-400 mt-8 pt-4 border-t border-neutral-700">
 <p><strong></strong>This guide was created and reviewed by our editorial team. <a href="/about/" class="text-emerald-600 hover:underline">Learn more about how we work</a>.</p>
 </div>

 <!-- FAQ Section -->
 <section class="mt-12 mb-8">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
 <div class="space-y-4">
 <details class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700 group" open>
 <summary class="text-lg font-semibold text-white cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">What is the fastest way to learn English grammar?<span class="text-emerald-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mt-3 leading-relaxed">Combine short daily study sessions with active practice. Learn one grammar point at a time (for example, present simple tense), then write 5 sentences using it, read a short article that uses it, and speak it aloud. 20-30 minutes a day beats 3 hours on the weekend.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700 group">
 <summary class="text-lg font-semibold text-white cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">Can I learn English grammar without memorizing rules?<span class="text-emerald-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mt-3 leading-relaxed">Partly. Input-based learning (reading and listening to lots of English) teaches you grammar patterns intuitively. But for faster progress, especially at B1 and B2 levels, combining input with explicit rule study produces the best results. Most learners benefit from knowing why a rule works, not just that it does.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700 group">
 <summary class="text-lg font-semibold text-white cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">How long does it take to master English grammar?<span class="text-emerald-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mt-3 leading-relaxed">Reaching B2 grammar mastery typically takes 300-600 hours of focused study, or roughly 6-12 months with daily practice. Basic conversational grammar (A2 level) can be reached in 100-150 hours. Advanced fluency with complex structures like conditionals and subjunctives usually takes 2-3 years.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700 group">
 <summary class="text-lg font-semibold text-white cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">What are the most important grammar rules for beginners?<span class="text-emerald-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mt-3 leading-relaxed">Focus on: (1) Subject-verb-object order, (2) Present simple vs present continuous, (3) Past simple for completed actions, (4) Articles a/an/the, (5) Common prepositions in/on/at, and (6) Basic question formation. These six areas cover most everyday communication.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-neutral-800 rounded-xl p-5 border border-neutral-700 group">
 <summary class="text-lg font-semibold text-white cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">Should I use a tutor to learn grammar or study alone?<span class="text-emerald-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="text-neutral-300 mt-3 leading-relaxed">Both work, but a tutor accelerates progress significantly. Self-study is enough for learning rules, but a tutor catches mistakes you would never notice alone and gives you speaking practice. A good hybrid is self-study plus 1-2 tutor lessons per week for correction and conversation.</p>
 </details>
 </div>
 </section>

 <aside class="mt-12 mb-4 p-6 bg-slate-900/60 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl">
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-4">Related guides</h3>
 <ul class="space-y-2 text-base">
 <li><a href="/guides/best-english-tutors-for-beginners/" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300">Best English Tutors for Beginners</a></li>
 <li><a href="/guides/best-english-apps-for-beginners/" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300">Best English Apps for Beginners</a></li>
 <li><a href="/guides/common-english-mistakes/" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300">Common English Mistakes</a></li>
 <li><a href="/guides/how-to-choose-english-tutor/" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300">How to Choose an English Tutor</a></li>
 </ul>
 <p class="mt-5 pt-5 border-t border-slate-700 text-sm text-slate-300">Want to test 1 on 1 lessons before paying? <a href="/reviews/see-guru/" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300 underline">See Guru</a>gives 3 free lessons with certified teachers, no card required.
 </p>
 </aside>

 </main>

 <Footer />
</Base>
